Three vaccination strategies are researched.
First, researchers are trying to create a whole virus vaccine.
The use of such a virus, whether inactive or dead, is intended to cause a rapid immune response from the human body in the event of a new infection with COVID-19.
A second strategy, based on subunit vaccines, is to create a vaccine that sensitizes the immune system to certain subunits of the virus.
In the case of SARS-CoV-2, these research focuses on specular protein S that helps the virus to infiltrate into the ACE 2 enzyme receptor.
A third strategy is that of nuclear acid-based vaccines (ADN or RNA vaccination, a new vaccination technique).
Experimental vaccines resulting from all these strategies should be tested in terms of safety and effectiveness. On 16 March 2020, the first clinical trial of a vaccine started with four volunteers in Seattle.
